scuss these three increasingly important constituencies. The entire book has been revised and updated, and a new introduction offers a global, comparative overview of the citizenship status of migrant domestic workers. Servants of Globalization remains the defining work on the international division of reproductive labor.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 15. Sep 2020) 0aFilipinosxEmploymentzForeign countries. 0aForeign workers, Filipino. 0aGlobalizationxSocial aspects. 0aWomen household employees. 0aWomenxEmploymentzForeign countries. 4aFilipinos. 4aItaly. 4aMigration. 4aPhilippines. 4aUnited States. 4adomestic work. 4agender. 4aglobalization. 4ainternational division of reproductive labor. 4awomen's migration. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Emigration & Immigration.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311070398640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978080479618740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780804796187423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780804796187.jpg  a978-3-11-070398-6  SUP Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aGBV-deGruyter-alles